FLUXC(1)                    User Commands                   FLUXC(1)

NAME
       fluxc - Flux heterogeneous optimizing compiler for C and Hyperdimensional Computing (HDC) code

SYNOPSIS
       fluxc --target=TARGET [-o OUTPUT_FILE] [-n BINARY_NAME] [--vectorize] INPUT_FILE...

DESCRIPTION
       fluxc is an ahead-of-time optimizing compiler that translates high-level Flux C and Flux HDC source code into optimized binaries, libraries, or hardware modules for heterogeneous target platforms. It integrates tightly with the flux_llvm_backend to deliver hardware-specific optimizations including automatic vectorization, cross-compilation, and kernel tuning for CPUs, GPUs, embedded systems, and kernel extensions.

OPTIONS
       --target=TARGET
              Required. Specify the target compilation platform. Valid target values are documented in the TARGETS section below.

       -o OUTPUT_FILE
              Write the compiled output to the file specified by OUTPUT_FILE. If omitted, a default filename derived from the input source and target platform will be used.

       -n BINARY_NAME
              Set the base name for the compiled output binary or library, overriding the default name generated from the input source file. Most commonly used for WebAssembly, CUDA, and Fortran library targets.

       --vectorize
              Enable automatic vectorization of loops and arithmetic operations for supported target platforms. Automatically disabled for non-vectorizable targets such as eBPF and minimal RISC-V builds.

TARGETS
       avx512   Optimize for 512-bit Advanced Vector Extensions (AVX-512) x86-64 CPU instruction sets, delivering maximum throughput for server and desktop x86 hardware.
       fortran  Compile to portable Fortran object files or static/shared libraries compatible with standard GNU/Intel Fortran toolchains.
       native   Compile for the host CPU’s native instruction set, automatically detecting and enabling all supported hardware features of the current machine.
       cuda     Generate NVIDIA CUDA device code (PTX format) optimized for modern NVIDIA GPU compute architectures (sm_70 and newer).
       wasm     Compile to WebAssembly binary format, compatible with all major web browsers and WASI runtime environments.
       ebpf     Generate Extended Berkeley Packet Filter (eBPF) kernel module code for Linux kernel networking, tracing, and security workloads.
       riscv    Compile to 64-bit RISC-V general-purpose machine code, supporting both embedded and enterprise-class RISC-V hardware.

EXAMPLES
       Example 1: Compile Flux C source to AVX-512 optimized object file
              Command:
                  $ fluxc --target=avx512 -o libfft.o fft_flux.c
              Output:
                  Optimizing for AVX-512 instruction set...
                  Auto-vectorized 92% of loop operations
                  Output written to libfft.o: 18.2KB, 417 optimized instructions

       Example 2: Compile Flux HDC source to vectorized WebAssembly module with custom name
              Command:
                  $ fluxc --target=wasm --vectorize -n flux_hdc_web flux_hdc_ops.hdc
              Output:
                  Enabled auto-vectorization for WASM target
                  Compiled HDC source to web-compatible binary
                  Output written to flux_hdc_web.wasm: 7.9KB, 6.8k vectorized memory operations

       Example 3: Compile Flux C network code to eBPF kernel module
              Command:
                  $ fluxc --target=ebpf -o firewall_kern.o network_flux.c
              Output:
                  Targeting eBPF kernel version 5.10+
                  Verified eBPF compatibility for packet filtering routines
                  Output written to firewall_kern.o: 3.2KB, 129 optimized eBPF instructions

BENCHMARKS
       Fluxc delivers industry-leading throughput for optimized workloads:
       •  22.3 billion operations per second for AVX-512 optimized linear algebra routines
       •  5.36 billion operations per second for compiled batch HDC inference jobs

SEE ALSO
       flux_llvm_backend(1), flux_hdc(1)

